																		Author Overview
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/weizhong" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1777811); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1777811&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164264" alt="weizhong" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1777811)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/weizhong" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1777811); return false;" >weizhong</a></span> <span class="odate time_1394321298 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Mar 2014 23:28</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1986923">
									

<p>This tale actually arose from <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-763409/recreation-and-morale" target="_blank">this discussion</a> on the forums that got me thinking about how exactly the Foundation handles events like this.</p>
<p>Now, the reason why this contains two relatively under-appreciated SCP's is because it was originally written for the UAC, but I decided not to post this for the contest, seeing as the main topic in this tale isn't the SCP's themselves, but rather, their effect on the researcher.</p>
<p>Thanks to all of chat for reading this, and also their many attempts to name this piece.</p>
<p>Also, if you know where these guys are from, bonus points to you.</p>

							</div>

								
