    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-1987455">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-1987455">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1987455)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1987455">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1361261"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1394393683 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 Mar 2014 19:34</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1987455">
									

<p>In terms of the article's logistics, a lot of what's going on feels silly. If the experiment with the photo booth was to simply find out whether killing the original had any effect, there surely was a better way involving less risk to everyone involved than just having a guard immediately blowing the D-Class subject's head off immediately. If the intent was &quot;hmmm, what's going to happen if we kill a person that happens to look exactly like the test subject, will they be agitated and scared&quot;, don't hang out by the phone waiting for that Nobel, doctors.</p>
<p>And the thing with the spoon. So they wait for the spoon to snap the person's spine, and then immediately afterward the doctor's all like &quot;tell me how you feel about that&quot;. C'mon. Also, I have to note that if the reason we're seemingly killing people for no reason is &quot;sample size&quot;, you're going to need a hell of a lot more than 10 people to establish that. I would imagine that the Foundation has other methods of testing, or tries to find out other things about items like this, since I can't imagine the Foundation is killing thousands of people a week in the name of testing Safe class objects.</p>
<p>I'm also not certain about the whole &quot;Moral Ambiguity Disorder&quot; thing. It seems like what would be happening is a whole lot of researchers with PTSD on the site; I don't know that the Foundation needed to invent a brand-new disorder to explain people being traumatized. And then of course it's all fixable with game nights and Christmas parties. You spend the first part of the article repeatedly telling us how awful and horrible the things the doctor is doing, and the payoff doesn't seem to recognize the supposed enormity of cruelty involved in the experimentation at all.</p>

							</div>

								
					
