			<div class="content" id="post-content-1987576">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Can't&nbsp;I&nbsp;just&nbsp;be&nbsp;lazy?&nbsp;:|</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Responses</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>He glanced at the testing chamber from within the observation room. The photobooth sat inside, as innocent as could be. A waiting D-class stood in front of it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Your sentences are all &quot;X did Y&quot;, not to mention the last two are fairly short and feel choppy. They don't flow together, in other words.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>“Please enter SCP-715 and take a photo, D-129012,” Louef instructed.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Don't eschew &quot;said&quot;.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>D-129012 strolled in. “Hey, guys, this thing is busted,” the voice came from inside. “I’m trying to use it, but it’s not giving me any photos.”</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Again, short sentences with basically the same structure, feeling choppy. That dialogue tag is slightly irregular; why not say <em>his</em> voice, or why not make him actually say it, instead of his voice saying it?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The somewhat confused looking D-129012 left the booth, and was stopped in front of the SCP object.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>There's a lot of this, too, &quot;the adverb adjective noun&quot; phrases. That's a really short-hand way to impart information, and it doesn't really draw the reader in. Same goes for &quot;his clone&quot; later on.</p>
<p>That's basically all the error types, just continued on again and again throughout that first scene. I did also have an issue with</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The test subject’s head snapped backwards in a shower of gore.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That's just a little over the top, same with the clone screaming a scream of &quot;misery and terror&quot; later on.</p>
</div>
</div>
